INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c1ec3f47-fedd-4010-8158-27f55ad66129',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GitHub Actions vs. Jenkins — Translating Jenkinsfiles, Shared Libraries, and Agent Config$escape$,
  $escape$If you're inheriting a Jenkins pipeline or migrating one, here's how the mental model maps to GitHub Actions. A Jenkinsfile is Jenkins' workflow-as-code — its direct equivalent is `.github/workflows/*.yml`. Both live in-repo and define CI/CD declaratively, but Jenkinsfile uses a Groovy DSL while GitHub Actions uses YAML.

Jenkins' `agent { docker { image 'node:20' } }` maps to a `container: node:20` key under a job definition. For bare metal, Jenkins agents register via JNLP or SSH; GitHub self-hosted runners register with a token and are referenced by label: `runs-on: [self-hosted, linux, x64]`.

Shared libraries (`@Library('my-lib')`) centralize reusable pipeline logic across teams. GitHub Actions' equivalent is reusable workflows (`workflow_call` trigger) or composite actions stored in a separate repo and pinned via `uses: org/lib/.github/workflows/deploy.yml@v2`. Unlike Jenkins shared libraries — which are Groovy classes with full imperative logic — GitHub reusable workflows are pure YAML with typed `inputs`.

Jenkins' `parallel {}` stages translate to sibling jobs or `matrix:` strategies. Critical difference: GitHub Actions jobs don't share a workspace — pass data between jobs with `actions/upload-artifact` and `actions/download-artifact`.$escape$,
  $escape$# Jenkins: agent { docker { image 'node:20' } } + @Library('shared-lib')
# GitHub Actions equivalent:
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    container:
      image: node:20
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      # Jenkins shared library → composite action from separate repo
      - uses: org/shared-actions/.github/actions/setup-node@v2
        with:
          node-version: '20'
      - run: npm ci && npm test
      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        with:
          name: dist
          path: dist/$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
