INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5d51e443-362d-421b-857b-ee7a403a3b2e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GitHub Actions Secrets — Vault Integration, Env Scopes, and What Never to Hardcode$escape$,
  $escape$GitHub Actions exposes secrets via `${{ secrets.MY_SECRET }}` — never via env vars you define inline. Hardcoding tokens in workflow YAML is a critical mistake: they appear in PR diffs, fork runs, and `actions/checkout` history. Use repository, environment, or organization-level secrets depending on blast radius. Environment secrets (Settings → Environments) gate values behind deployment protection rules — ideal for production credentials. For dynamic secrets or short-lived tokens, integrate HashiCorp Vault using `hashicorp/vault-action`: it authenticates via GitHub's OIDC token (`id-token: write` permission required), fetches secrets at runtime, and never stores them in your repo. For AWS, skip static IAM keys entirely — use `aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials` with OIDC to assume a role. Secrets are masked in logs automatically, but structured output (JSON, base64) can leak them — always pipe sensitive output through `jq` or mask manually with `echo "::add-mask::$VALUE"`. Never pass secrets as positional CLI args; they appear in `ps` output. Use environment variables or stdin instead.$escape$,
  $escape$jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    permissions:
      id-token: write
      contents: read
    environment: production
    steps:
      - uses: hashicorp/vault-action@v3
        with:
          url: ${{ secrets.VAULT_ADDR }}
          method: jwt
          role: github-actions-role
          secrets: |
            secret/data/prod db_password | DB_PASSWORD ;
            secret/data/prod api_key    | API_KEY
      - name: mask dynamic value
        run: echo "::add-mask::$DB_PASSWORD"$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
